[[File:International Dyslexia Association Logo.png|thumb|International Dyslexia Association]]

The '''International Dyslexia Association''' ('''IDA''') is a [[non-profit]] education and advocacy organization devoted to issues surrounding [[dyslexia]]. It is based in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], United States.<ref>[http://www.ninds.nih.gov/find_people/voluntary_orgs/volorg120.htm International Dyslexia Association], [[National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke]], USA.</ref>

The International Dyslexia Association serves individuals with dyslexia, their families, and professionals in the field. It has 9,000 members <ref>{{cite web | url=http://eida.org/ida-financial-reports/ | title=International Dyslexia Association financial reports | publisher=IDA | year=2015 | accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> and it operates with more than 40 branches <ref>{{cite web | url=http://eida.org/ida-branches/ | title=International Dyslexia Association branches | publisher=IDA | year=2015 | accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> throughout the United States and Canada, and has global partners in twenty-one countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://eida.org/partners-2/ | title=International Dyslexia Association partners | publisher=IDA | year=2015 | accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> IDA has an all-volunteer Board of Directors.

The IDA provides information about dyslexia on its website, publishes a [[peer-review]]ed [[scientific journal]] (''Annals of Dyslexia''), publishes newsletter updates to members; provides referral services to individuals and professionals; advocates for the rights of individuals with dyslexia through the legal and Federal legislative systems. IDA is working to match increasing demand for teacher training and teacher preparation aligned with the IDA Knowledge & Practice standards. The IDA provides peer reviewed Fact Sheets <ref>{{cite web | url=http://eida.org/fact-sheets/ | title=International Dyslexia Association Fact Sheets | publisher=IDA | year=2015 | accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> and access to regional experts that together help support [[Decoding Dyslexia|grassroots]] state and regional educational and advocacy efforts.

